How can I determine the length of the longest increasing subsequence of an array that starts and ends with prime numbers, and has a length greater than or equal to 3, given that the input array may contain multiple prime numbers? Can you provide a Scala code solution that involves multiple steps of reasoning?
Here is the given input array: 
arr = [2, 7, 10, 3, 8, 11, 13, 17, 9, 5, 19]
To solve this problem, we can start by finding all prime numbers in the input array and storing them in a separate array. Then, we can use dynamic programming to find the longest increasing subsequence that starts and ends with a prime number. Here is a Scala code solution that implements these steps: 
```scala
val arr = Array(2, 7, 10, 3, 8, 11, 13, 17, 9, 5, 19)
// Find all prime numbers in the input array
val primes = arr.filter(num => (2 until num).forall(i => num % i != 0))
// Initialize dynamic programming array with all elements set to 1
val dp = Array.fill(primes.length, primes.length)(1)
// Fill the dp array using dynamic programming
for {
  i <- 1 until primes.length
  j <- 0 until i
} {
  if (arr.indexOf(primes(i)) > arr.indexOf(primes(j)) && dp(j)(i) < dp(i)(j) + 1) {
    dp(i)(j) = dp(i)(j) + 1
  }
}
// Find the longest increasing subsequence that starts and ends with a prime number
val result = (for {
  i <- 0 until primes.length
  j <- 0 until primes.length
  if (dp(i)(j) >= 3 && primes(i) == primes(j))
} yield dp(i)(j)).max
// Print the result
println(result)
```
This code should output 5, which is the length of the longest increasing subsequence that starts and ends with a prime number in the given input array.

