How can I modify my existing PHP code to insert punctuation marks into a given sentence? In addition to adding a period at the end of the sentence and a comma after a specific word, I also need to ensure that any existing punctuation marks are not affected. For instance, if the sentence is "John said, 'I am not hungry'", the code should only add a period at the end of the sentence and a comma after "said". Can you provide an updated PHP code snippet that satisfies these requirements?
Here's an example PHP code snippet that achieves the desired result:
<?php
$sentence = "John said, 'I am not hungry'";
$punctuation = array(".", ",", "!", "?", ";", ":", "-", "(", ")", "[", "]");
$words = preg_split('/([\s]+)/', $sentence, -1, PREG_SPLIT_DELIM_CAPTURE);
$last_word_index = count($words) - 2;
if (in_array($words[$last_word_index], $punctuation)) {
  $last_word_index--;
}
$words[$last_word_index] .= ",";
$words[count($words) - 1] = ".";
echo implode("", $words);
?>
This code splits the sentence into individual words and punctuation marks, and then adds a comma after the last word before the final punctuation mark (if there is one). Finally, it adds a period at the end of the sentence.

