What modifications can be made to a quicksort algorithm implemented on a SQL database to improve its efficiency and speed? Here is the original SQL code:
CREATE FUNCTION quicksort(arr int[]) RETURNS int[] AS $$
BEGIN
    IF array_length(arr,1) <= 1 THEN
        RETURN arr;
    END IF;
    SELECT arr[1] INTO pivot;
    SELECT array_agg(x ORDER BY x) INTO left FROM unnest(arr[2:]) x WHERE x <= pivot;
    SELECT array_agg(x ORDER BY x) INTO right FROM unnest(arr[2:]) x WHERE x > pivot;
    RETURN ARRAY(SELECT * FROM unnest(quicksort(left), pivot, quicksort(right)));
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;
And here is a modified version of the code with improvements:
CREATE FUNCTION quicksort(arr int[]) RETURNS int[] AS $$
BEGIN
    IF array_length(arr,1) <= 1 THEN
        RETURN arr;
    END IF;
    SELECT arr[1] INTO pivot;
    SELECT array_agg(x ORDER BY x) INTO left FROM unnest(arr[2:]) x WHERE x <= pivot;
    SELECT array_agg(x ORDER BY x) INTO right FROM unnest(arr[2:]) x WHERE x > pivot;
    SELECT ARRAY(SELECT * FROM unnest(left) UNION ALL SELECT pivot UNION ALL SELECT * FROM unnest(right))) INTO result;
    RETURN result;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;
This version of the code uses UNION ALL to combine the left and right subarrays with the pivot element, instead of creating a new array with unnest(). It also reduces the number of SELECT statements needed and eliminates the need for recursion, resulting in faster and more efficient sorting.

