How can object-oriented programming be beneficial in terms of code organization and reusability in C#? Could you provide an example of how inheritance can be used to achieve this?
Here is an example of how inheritance can be used in C#:
public class Animal
{
    public virtual void Move()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("This animal moves.");
    }
}
public class Dog : Animal
{
    public override void Move()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("This dog runs.");
    }
}
public class Bird : Animal
{
    public override void Move()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("This bird flies.");
    }
}
In this example, the Animal class serves as the base class, while the Dog and Bird classes inherit from it. By using inheritance, we can avoid writing redundant code for the Move method, as both the Dog and Bird classes can simply override it with their own unique behavior.
In addition, by using polymorphism, we can treat instances of both the Dog and Bird classes as instances of the Animal class, allowing for greater code flexibility and easier maintenance.

